Democracy without popular connection
Something has happened to democracy in the sense that the government is elected by the people, and this has happened everywhere in the world.
Somehow people have lost faith in elections.
Voter turnout is declining in many countries; in the case of elections for the European Parliament, the voter turnout was so absurdly low that the legitimacy of the election result is questionable.
Aside from voter turnout, we have become accustomed to accepting parties or candidates who receive 25% of the votes as "winners".
From Holland through Finland to Argentina and Japan, majority governments are formed on the basis of minorities.
Even the apparent exceptions do not prove the opposite.
Only a few American Presidents have been elected by more than 10% of the electorate. In fact, half of the voters in the USA have not even registered to participate in the election; of those who registered, half do not vote; of those who vote, less than half vote for the election winner.
Even Tony Blair's "dam-breaking" majority in the British House of Commons stands on shaky ground: The Labour Party received only slightly over 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002, with a voter turnout of 60%.
Thus, only 24% of the total electorate supported Blair's party.
In most countries, elections look quite different now than they did twenty, or even fifty, years ago.
What has happened?
An answer may be that voters distrust the political parties.
The electoral democracy functions in most countries on the basis of mediation by organizations that put forward candidates who stand for certain packages of political options, for a "manifesto" or a "campaign platform."
For a number of reasons, this long-established practice no longer works.
Ideological party programs have lost their power; voters no longer accept the packages put together by the parties, they want to select and choose something for themselves.
Furthermore, political parties have become machines composed of tightly organized cores of insiders.
The paradox here is that the parties have become even more clique-like with the loss of their specific ideological orientation.
It is more important to belong to them than to share their specific beliefs.
Such developments have distanced the parties from the voters.
Because most people do not want to belong to any particular party, only a minority is now playing the party game.
Thus, public suspicion of political parties is increasing, not least because - like in professional sports - it is expensive to participate.
If the costs are borne by the taxpayer, this is resented.
However, without financial support from the state, parties would have to find money through channels that are often quite questionable, if not even illegal.
Many of the major political scandals of the last decades began with the financing of parties and their candidates.
Other indicators - such as the clear decline in memberships - confirm that parties have become unpopular.
Nevertheless, parties are indispensable for a electoral democracy.
The result is an obvious separation between the visible political actors and the electorate.
Because parties are active in parliaments, the effects of this separation concern one of the crucial institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that parliaments represent them and thus have the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, a second, quite independent development comes into play.
People today are more impatient than ever before.
As consumers, they are used to immediate satisfaction.
But as voters, they have to wait before they can feel the results of the election they made at the ballot box.
Sometimes they never see the desired results.
Democracy needs time not only for elections, but also for discussions and careful deliberation.
The consumer as a voter, however, will not accept this and thus turns away.
There are alternatives. Yet, each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
"Direct action" through demonstrations has become a regular and often effective event.
For less mobile people, this could be replaced by the possibility of expressing their opinion electronically; this ranges from internet chat pages to electronic messages to political leaders.
Then there are the non-governmental organizations. They often have undemocratic internal structures, yet seem to be more closely connected to the citizens.
Furthermore, there is naturally the possibility of completely disengaging and leaving politics to the experts in order to focus on other priorities in life.
The latter carries the greatest risks, because it fosters the creeping authoritarianism that is a sign of our time.
However, the other signs of the separation between politics and citizens also create a rather uncertain situation, because no one can anymore say how representative the prevailing views are.
Some would like to cut through the knot by means of more direct democracy.
But a lasting connection between leaders and the led cannot be established by reducing public discussion to simple voting alternatives.
There would be much to be said for sticking to the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and trying to link them again more closely with the citizenry.
After all, unpopular parties and declining voter participation could turn out to be only temporary phenomena.
New parties could emerge and inject more life into elections and representative governments.
Yet this would probably not be enough to restore the general legitimacy that elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the first concern of all those for whom the constitution of freedom is dear must be to rethink democracy and its institutions.
